le":"1140–preminula","1206":"1206.","1190":"1190","about 1190":"oko 1190.","1175":"1175.","1230":"1230","1185":"1185.","1140":"1140","1160":"1160.","1170":"1170","England":"England","Groton, Cosford, Suffolk, England":"Groton, Suffolk, Engleska, United Kingdom"},"cs":{"1160–1206":"1160–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Zesnulá","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1140–1175":"1140–1175","1140–Female":"1140–Zesnulá","1206":"1206","1190":"1190","about 1190":"okolo 1190","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","England":"Anglie","Groton, Cosford, Suffolk, England":"Groton, Suffolk, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"1160–1206":"1160–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Afdød","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1140–1175":"1140–1175","1140–Female":"1140–Afdød","1206":"1206","1190":"1190","about 1190":"omkring 1190","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","England":"England","Groton, Cosford, Suffolk, England":"Groton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1160–1206":"1160–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Overleden","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1140–1175":"1140–1175","1140–Female":"1140–Overleden","1206":"1206","1190":"1190","about 1190":"circa 1190","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","England":"England","Groton, Cosford, Suffolk, England":"Groton, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1160–1206":"1160–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1140–1175":"1140–1175","1140–Female":"1140–Deceased","1206":"1206","1190":"1190","about 1190":"about 1190","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","England":"England","Groton, Cosford, Suffolk, England":"Groton, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beaumont","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Gilles, Gaetan, Honore, Jacques, Jean-Guy, Marcel.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of the five places in Normandy or several others elsewhere in France so named. The placename comes from Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>mont</i> ‘hill’. There are also places in England so named under Norman influence in Cumberland, Lancashire, and Essex, the last of which changed its name in the 12th century from <i>Fulepet</i> ‘foul pit’ to <i>Bealmont</i> ‘beautiful hill’; these may also have given rise to the surname. The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When William de Beaumont II was born in 1160, in England, his father, Mr Godfrey de Beaumont, was 21 and his mother, Mrs Godfrey de Beaumont, was 21. He married Joan Barsham in 1185. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1206, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1160–1206":"1160–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1140–1175":"1140–1175","1140–Female":"1140–Surnud","1206":"1206","1190":"1190","about 1190":"umbes 1190","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","England":"England","Groton, Cosford, Suffolk, England":"Groton, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1160–1206":"1160–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1140–1175":"1140–1175","1140–Female":"1140–Kuollut","1206":"1206","1190":"1190","about 1190":"noin 1190","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","England":"England","Groton, Cosford, Suffolk, England":"Groton, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1160–1206":"1160–1206","1170–Female":"1170–Décédée","1190–1230":"1190–1230","1140–1175":"1140–1175","1140–Female":"1140–Décédée","1206":"1206","1190":"1190","about 1190":"environ 1190","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1185":"1185","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","England":"Angleterre","Groton, Cosford, Suffolk, England":"Groton, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque William de Beaumont II est né en 1160, à Angleterre, son père, Mr Godfrey de Beaumont, avait 21 ans et sa mère, Mrs Godfrey de Beaumont, a